<h2>Francos Pizza</h2>

<p>
In 1956, 13-year-old Frank Tedesco immigrated from Cosenza, Italy, with his mother and four siblings to join Frank’s father, who had already been working in Windsor. Although his father wanted him to remain in school, Frank struggled with the language barrier and chose to enter the workforce instead. By 1958, with jobs in Windsor becoming limited, Frank moved to Oakville to work in construction. During this time, he began cooking for himself and his roommates, developing skills that would later shape his career in the restaurant industry. When Frank was 30, he returned to Windsor and secured a job as a dishwasher at Volcano’s Pizzeria. He quickly worked his way up to becoming a short-order cook, where he learned both the craft of pizza-making and the fundamentals of running a successful restaurant. In 1963, Frank entered the restaurant industry as an owner, first opening the Colosseo Restaurant on Ottawa Street. Months later, he sold his shares and leased the Milano, formerly known as the Normandy Grill. </p>

<p>
By 1973, Frank recognized that many customers who came for spaghetti and pizza felt out of place at Milanos. In response, he opened Franco’s Spaghetti Factory and Pizza House as a family-friendly establishment. During this period, Milano remained one of the largest pizzerias in Windsor, serving Chrysler workers near the factory gates. By 1976, however, managing both restaurants had become increasingly difficult, leading Frank to sell Milano and focus entirely on Franco’s. By the 1980s, Franco’s had become a pizza giant in Windsor, reportedly selling as many as 900 pizzas a day and up to 3,000 on weekends. In 1984, a Windsor Star article reported that Frank expected annual sales to exceed $3 million, equivalent to approximately $8 million in 2026 when adjusted for inflation. At the time, the restaurant employed 140 people, with as many as 22 cooks working on Friday nights. Despite this growth, Franco’s maintained its family-oriented atmosphere, with Frank’s children working in the kitchen as helpers. As early as 1985, former Windsor residents and Americans reportedly craved Windsor-style pizza. One Windsor Star article from that year noted that a man from Calgary stopped in Windsor specifically to eat the city’s pizza. 
</p>

<p>
After 33 years of ownership, Frank sold Franco’s to the Donato family, who have continued operating the business ever since. By 1997, Franco’s had expanded to five locations, with 3 current locations in 2026. Regardless of these changes, Franco’s continues to hold an important place in Windsor’s pizza history, particularly for its reputation as one of the city’s top pizzerias during the 1980s. The restaurant’s motto, “family to family,” reflects the broader culture of Windsor’s pizza industry, one rooted in immigrant labour and family environments that connected people in Windsor and beyond.
</p>
</div>


