            <h2>Naples Pizza</h2>

            <p>
                In 1970, 13-year-old Tony Bahceli immigrated with his family from Cyprus to Windsor, seeking refuge from growing political tensions. Tony’s father, Kemal, instilled a strong work ethic that would shape his future career. Tony secured his first job at the Harveys on Wyandotte Street West, where he learned the fundamentals of the food service industry. After gaining experience in the restaurant business, Tony began working at Chrysler Canada, where he quickly advanced to a supervisory position. Tony decided in 1983 that it was time to start his own business. The following year, he opened the first Naples Pizza location. Tony chose the name “Naples” because of the city’s reputation for exceptional food. The official website for Naples Pizza claims that its first location opened in 1984 in East Windsor. However, a 2006 article from the Windsor Star states Naples was first opened in Amherstburg. The first location of Naples Pizza could not be independently verified; however, a 1990s advertisement showed two locations on Dougall and Lauzon Rd.
            </p>

            <p>
                Canadian Bread Bakers, a wholesale bakery. By 1995, Naples Pizza had grown to nine locations. When asked about the secret to his success, Tony credited his family as the foundation of the business. Continued expansion brought the company to 17 locations by 2006, including a restaurant in London, Ontario, and to 19 locations by 2010, including a now-closed Sarnia location. Today, Naples Pizza operates 12 locations, many of which are franchised, while still maintaining the traditional Windsor-style pizza recipe. Like many other Windsor pizzerias, Naples was the product of a hard-working immigrant who built a business off of a tradtional recipe and instilled the importance of family.
            </p>

        </div>

